  "slug": "chicken-paprikash",
  "title": "Chicken paprikash",
  "subtitle": "Hungarian braise with sweet paprika and soured cream.",
  "excerpt": "Chicken thighs braised in a deep red sauce of slow-cooked onion, sweet Hungarian paprika, and tomato. Soured cream stirred in at the end gives the dish its pink sheen. Eaten with buttered noodles or nokedli dumplings.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The dish appears in Károly Gundel's classical Hungarian Cookery (1934, public domain in Hungary) and earlier in regional Magyar cookery manuscripts. The household ratio of paprika to onion to liquid follows that tradition.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Hungarian paprika is the dish. Édesnemes (the sweet noble grade) gives a deep red colour and a soft warmth. Avoid pre-ground paprika that has sat in a supermarket aisle for months; the flavour fades quickly. A fresh tin from a Hungarian or Polish deli is worth the hunt.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The technique is straightforward. Onion cooked down soft, paprika stirred in off the heat (so it doesn't burn), chicken added back to the pan with stock, simmered for 30 minutes, finished with soured cream. The traditional accompaniment is nokedli, the small Hungarian dumpling; buttered tagliatelle or wide egg noodles also work.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
