      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A heavy lidded casserole or Dutch oven of around 4 litres holds the chicken in a single layer.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown the chicken",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pat {{chicken-thigh}} of chicken thighs dry. Season with {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt and {{black-pepper}} of pepper. Melt {{lard}} of lard in the casserole over medium-high heat. Brown the chicken skin-side down for 6 minutes until deep gold; turn and cook 2 minutes more. Lift onto a plate.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Soften the onions",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pour off all but 2 tablespoons of fat. Add {{onion}} of chopped onion and a pinch of salt. Cook over medium heat for 12 minutes, stirring often, until soft and turning gold. Add {{garlic}} of garlic and {{pepper-red}} of chopped red pepper for 2 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the paprika off the heat",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pull the pan off the heat. Stir in {{paprika-sweet}} of sweet paprika and {{paprika-hot}} of hot paprika if using. The off-heat moment matters; paprika burns at high heat and turns bitter. Stir for 30 seconds, then add {{tomato}} of chopped tomato and pour in {{stock-chicken}} of stock.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Braise",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Return the chicken to the pan, skin side up. Bring to a simmer, cover, and cook for 30 minutes until the chicken is tender and pulls easily at the thigh joint.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Finish with soured cream",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lift the chicken onto a warm plate. Whisk {{soured-cream}} of soured cream with {{plain-flour}} of flour in a small bowl, then stir in a ladleful of hot sauce from the pan to temper it. Pour the soured-cream mixture back into the casserole and bring to a gentle simmer for 2 minutes; the flour stops the cream splitting. Return the chicken to the pan and turn to coat. Scatter with {{parsley-flat}} of chopped parsley.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Always pull the pan off the heat before the paprika goes in. Stir for no more than 30 seconds before liquid is added.",
              "cause": "Paprika burnt at high heat.",
              "symptom": "Sauce bitter and dark"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Temper the soured cream with a ladle of hot sauce in a bowl first. Whisk with a teaspoon of flour for added insurance against splitting.",
              "cause": "Cold soured cream added directly to a boiling pan.",
              "symptom": "Sauce split with white flecks"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use fresh Hungarian sweet paprika from a deli or specialist supplier. Supermarket budget brands lose flavour within months of grinding.",
              "cause": "Old or low-grade paprika.",
              "symptom": "Paprika tastes dusty and flat"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Cover for the first 20 minutes, uncover for the last 10 to reduce. The final soured-cream stage also thickens.",
              "cause": "Lid kept on the entire braise.",
              "symptom": "Sauce too thin"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Paprikás csirke is a household dinner across Hungary, served with nokedli, the country's small egg-flour dumplings pinched off the side of a board into boiling water. The American-Hungarian diaspora kept the dish alive in cities like Cleveland and Pittsburgh. A glass of Tokaji dry or a light Hungarian red sits comfortably beside it.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
